The Prague Stock Exchange is sinking against closing.
After the steep drop in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
Transactions in ČEZ's shares reached almost half of the normal daily business.
At the beginning of Tuesday's business, the Prague Stock Exchange continued its collapse from Monday when it fell by a further six percentage points.
This time the reason for the break-in was on Wall Street.
In the Czech Republic, too, the reaction of the market to the outcome of the vote by the American House of Representatives, which had refused to support a stabilisation plan for the financial sector there.
Case of shares in Asia
On Tuesday, stocks on the Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic case, although the indices were able to offset some of the losses during the day.
The Hang Seng Stock Exchange index in Hong Kong lost almost four percentage points during the business day, but was later able to make up for some of the losses, reducing the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The index Hang Seng China Enterprises, which observed the movement of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, and markets were closed in Shanghai.
The shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but then decreased the losses to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange declined by 3.6 percent according to the index there.
"The timing for the rescue operation in the US is uncertain and will influence the financial markets worldwide," said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong currency agency.
Although it belongs to China, Hong Kong determines its monetary policy itself, independent of the Chinese Central Bank.
Hong Kong's interest rates are at the same level as those in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, American legislators should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible and adopt the draft financial system support.
Otherwise, it threatened that other countries would also be affected by the collapse.
A Blutbad of American Shares
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the plan to support the financial system, for which up to 700 billion dollars (almost 12 trillion Kč) should be spent.
The legislators thus ignored President George Bush's request to support the plan.
Bush believes that the plan would regulate the root causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilise the entire economy.
America's shares suffered a bloodbath on Monday, and the main stock indices recorded the largest drop in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell by almost seven percent, with a similar break-in last recorded in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there was hardly any indication that the draft would not get through in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress makes concession: US government is allowed to pump 700 billion dollars into banks
The senior representatives of the American Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of financial assistance agreement for the American financial system.
The vote will take place at the beginning of next week.
The US legislators made a breakthrough in talks on the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of financial assistance to the US financial system to the tune of $700 billion (about $12 trillion).
However, this does not mean a victory.
Congressmen still have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they are allowed to publish and vote on the final version of the law.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated in the US Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, Barney Frank, Chairman of the Committee on Banking and Financial Services, said this to the agency Reuters.
According to various sources, the Senate could probably vote on the plan at the earliest on Wednesday.
According to economists, a communication on the adoption of the plan should be the first significant psychological factor for the revival of financial markets.
Afterwards, however, there was a "disenchantment" due to the complicated mechanisms that could help the markets in practice.
Paulson: The Plan Must Be Effective
"We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our different views on what a package to stabilise the market should look like," said Democrat Nancy Pelosi to the agency Bloomberg.
According to her, there could still be a final vote on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislators met with the American Finance Minister Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give the government fund its final form.
This provides for the purchase of unsaleable mortgage assets from financial companies that plunge financial firms into heavy losses and endanger the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and which must also be effective on the market.
The health plan must be continued even further, but I think we are at our goal," says Paulson.
A signal for Asian businesses
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to the Democratic Senator of Nevada, Harry Reid, the legislators are trying to reach a final agreement in Congress before Sunday.
The aim is to reassure investors of business in Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a congress decision could influence business on Monday.
To date, however, it is not quite clear when both chambers of the American Congress will vote on the law, and there is also uncertainty as to whether the negotiations at the last minute could still fail on a problem.
The legislators hope that it will be adopted in the next few days.
The law, however, will undergo some changes.
The total amount intended to help the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush demanded.
Congress, however, can block the distribution of the remaining money if it has the impression that the program does not fulfil its function, with another $100 billion and later with the final $350 billion.
Bush welcomes progress in negotiations
The President has a right of veto in this decision, but Congress can override its veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program has remained, based on obtaining finance for the purchase of bad mortgage securities whose value has fallen, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages.
"We've worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the law on Sunday, the Senate then on Monday," according to Republican senator Judd Gregg.
American President Bush was also satisfied with the progress.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said that Bush was satisfied with Saturday's progress and "estimates the mutual effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
The Chairman of the Banking Committee of the Senate Christopher Dodd, the senior negotiator, said that the legislators had agreed on a responsibility for the money program, the protection of taxpayers from losses, the completion of benefits and a timetable for financing the plan.
The new law is also intended to restrict the so-called golden parachutes for directors of the companies involved in the programme and to set up a committee to oversee the fund.
The Ministry of Finance is responsible for this.
"We have worked very hard on it and have made great progress towards an agreement that works and is important for the market and for all Americans," says Paulson.
The plan also expects help for homeowners who have problems repaying their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new mortgage rates that it buys, with the aim of reducing the monthly cost of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological aid
The proposed plan is a good idea after the main economist of Patria Finance David Marek, but implementation will be very difficult.
"That is because one does not know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets are bought up.
This will be crucial for how the financial sector and the government split the losses among themselves," said Marek to the iHNed.cz server this week.
Whether the plan is to be adopted now or early next week is not the decisive factor, Marek believes.
"It is much more important for Congressmen to agree to support the plan and to say goodbye as soon as possible.
The psychological importance of the agreement on the adoption is the most important at this moment," emphasized Marek.
Duel on knife edge: MP3 player against mobile phones.
We advise you on your choice
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls.
So, of course, it looks like it's better to buy just one phone.
Despite all this, there are plenty of reasons why you should get a stand-alone player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the claims of future owners.
I'm sure it's hard to buy a great expensive record player at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
Once such musical novelties do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this either.
However, if you have LPs with Art Rock, Jazz or Blues on the shelf, you probably dream of at least one of them.
This is also the case with music on travel, i.e. with compressed music, in a simplified way - music in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For one, it may not be acceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a player, but also a pink-floyd fan will hardly handle headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough room for everyone.
The selection is broad.
The lifespan of the batteries is also crucial.
Some good music players can play much more than just music, but what mobile phones can do is not even meaningful.
No modern device is as universal as the telephone.
Besides the primary functions, the phone and the simmer, it can play music and videos, record both, it has a better, sometimes a worse camera and can maybe also navigate.
And if you still include the smartphones and communicators, you almost have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a little miracle, because no fridge can barbecue and no TV can photograph.
But the universality of mobile phones also has disadvantages.
The more features you use on your phone, the more often you will have to reload it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Only a few mobile phones can play music for more than ten-twelve hours, mostly it is much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more powerful.
That's why you should expect the cheap phones to be able to play music for no more than a few hours.
If you make a phone call from time to time, you prefer to buy a charger for the office for safety - this also applies to more expensive devices.
For MP3 players, you won't have this problem, even the less good ones will last at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation with one charge.
Another problem is if you want to transfer the music to your phone.
Unfortunately, only a small part of the devices have a USB connection, besides, not every mobile phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, the music can be transferred directly to a storage medium, but only a few card readers can be done with the tiny memory cards used in mobile phones without any reduction.
Players do not require any special software except for exceptions (iPod).
You only need to feed the device with music from your PC via USB port.
Most mobile phones and players create a music library themselves, arranged according to the name of the performer, the title of the album, the genre or, for example, the user rating.
Some devices only represent the tree structure of the address directory, similar to Windows Explorer, some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, intelligent phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can do more
When choosing a specific device, you should inquire in particular about the lifespan of the battery, the storage capacity, the quality and the type of sound and, of course, also the ease of use.
Is music for you above all the backdrop and listen to it every day only briefly for example in the tram, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 files is enough.
Which almost every cell phone can really do.
You also don't have to control which music formats a mobile phone or a player can process.
MP3 create all, and most of the music you get will be just in this format.
The format is one of the most widely used, and most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format that Apple and its iPods use).
Better mobile phones also enable the purchase of music online.
You only need to access the corresponding pages of a provider (or another provider) via mobile Internet, and you can already purchase a song or album.
This service can in itself be a striking argument for why you should buy a music phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of the providers is bad and is mostly limited to fast radio hits.
The prices are not the lowest either.
In general, however, it is assumed that this type of music sales (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry the phone with them.
If you feel like listening to something, grab your phone in your jacket pocket while the player is forgotten at home.
However, it depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least a wireless hands-free device.
If not, you can rely on the built-in speaker that almost every mobile phone has, but only a few MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of the music phones will be in the price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns, you'll get a very decent Walkman.
The biggest handicap for most people will be that there are no normal headphones.
The best and technically most sophisticated telephones with a 3.5 mm opening for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the players lies in the ease of use.
The easiest - and not necessarily cheapest - players can really serve everyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity in operation with the previously normal cassette recorder or, for example, the record player is obvious.
There is no danger of a collision in the form of an erroneously employed mobile Internet and a subsequent horrendous bill for data transfers.
Which device should you grab now?
Also the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable storage media (type M2, microSD etc.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card, two thousand crowns are sufficient.
Attention, though.
The basic models usually only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones can also read 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, then grab Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to place more than 1100 crowns on the table.
Be among the more demanding listeners, prefer specialized mobile phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some of Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have stand-alone control buttons for MP3, and the ease of use is that of a single MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose phones from the Walkman series have the same user interface as the MP3 players sold individually, is the furthest.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, maximum up to 35 hours) provide you MP3 players of the above mentioned manufacturers.
The first virtual provider comes to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic to lower prices.
Maybe he won't be waiting much longer.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that Czech mobile operators are among the most expensive in Europe at all.
This was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the recent steps taken by the European Commission in the area of regulation of roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS will be cheaper from abroad than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a fight announcement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, since in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain about the fact that there is an extremely high level of competition on the Czech market.
Pavel Dvořák, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ), has often agreed that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has very many opportunities (by the way, it would probably hardly find any frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market resulted in a significant price reduction, which the classic mobile operators had to react to.
Even before such companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, there were similar voices to those in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, it doesn't take long to look for examples.
In February this we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider succeeded in attracting more than 100 thousand customers and thus becoming the country's five largest provider.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon among others in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that they can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to be able to function effectively, virtual providers need a lot less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually turn out to be low-cost companies - they offer cheap telephone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
In the UK, for example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobileking in Poland shows, it can also be quite a good move to rely on a non-clichéd target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a concept similar to that in Poland could take root in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone's spokesperson Miroslav Čepický also doubted this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of service provision."
In the Czech Republic, the mobile operators mean no chance
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile service provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
Mobilking will be more likely to enter the market in other countries in our region," says Jana Studničková, Press Spokesperson of the Penta Finance Group in a telephone conversation for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
For some time now, the GTS Novera group has been showing interest in launching a virtual mobile network provider, which wants to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the corporate customer sector.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed network services, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we were already able to achieve progress in the negotiations," said the press spokesman of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
Maybe better times are coming.
Non-official information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this has been surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specifics compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and reputable project in this area," says in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the Telefónica O2 press department.
Other suppliers also point to the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile Press Spokesperson Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on."
And she adds: "In the T-Mobile network, hardly any virtual provider will show up by the end of the year.
At this moment, we should already have a concrete offer to be able to think so in the short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure sharing.
This is precisely what we consider the best from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - with the providers in hand
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider would be more competitive, this would lead to lower prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that providers can pull together when it comes to something also proves the long back and forth about the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ came from T-Mobile when U:fon came on the market.
This is also demonstrated by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
Now, however, U:fon is just an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services."
Given this approach, however, the absolute disinterest of Czech regulators is surprising.
This is not just ČTÚ's attitude, which unfortunately - unlike the UK and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
The Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS) is the exclusive holder of the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, took its very typical attitude to this whole problem.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile service provider would be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile service provider and a virtual service provider through the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers," says Kristián Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS in his answer to our question.
Such a formulation would not surprise representatives of suppliers.
This is more than questionable by an authority that represents consumer interests and, among other things, seeks to ensure that no one abuses his position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual providers work normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not one of the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, the almost touching harmony of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions, is really shocking.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same price of petrol at the petrol stations is certainly only chance and the result of a fierce competition.
"The Authority has not found any evidence in this case suggesting anti-competitive action, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the suppliers has a dominant market position, so it does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for its actions on the market.
The necessary instruments for opening up the mobile market to virtual providers are probably also missing from the telecoms regulator," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, developed by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different perspective - the agreement of the network operator is always necessary for the market entry of a virtual provider.
And the mobile operator - logically - has the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if one does not go along with this argument, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are strikingly similar.
In this context, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) demonstrate that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The transfer of responsibility to ČTÚ is then a quite common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent amendment to the Telecommunications Act has failed to enforce the extension of ČTÚ's competence to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS need to know only too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay when no one's looking
For the time being, the functioning of any pseudovirtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but they are only partially public.
They are usually companies operating in the field of multi-level marketing.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others offer their own mobile telephone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar kind of resale.
"If there are cases that describe you, then it may be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which can lead to an end to cooperation with the corresponding company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not be talked about by those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an approach.
In fact, the activity of these companies does not result in negligible profits, but at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite everything, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card on their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot have full value over it like the normal customers of the mobile phone providers."
But this alone should at least seem strange to ČTÚ.
Another question for the ÚOHS also opens up.
If mobile providers close their eyes to such an approach, why are they blocking themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the supplier's statement that they do not know about them and that their terms and conditions would prohibit them.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been emphasised several times in the text, the market entry of virtual suppliers resulted in a significant fall in the price of the various services.
In virtually all countries, where virtual providers were created, traditional providers have tried to prevent their emergence virtually more or less.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - a market that was too small or too saturated, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the advanced countries, however, it was precisely at these moments that the regulatory bodies intervened, which by no means sought to safeguard the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was born, and this followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing themselves into the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that lack of clarity in competences is more than beneficial in these cases.
But let's not throw the shotgun in the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider soon appears, the Czech mobile phone market may soon start moving again.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will at last make no more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four versions of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem Where is my home country on the occasion of the day of Czech statehood.
The anthem was re-recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solo vocals, in choir version and in an instrumental version.
The vocal version was taken over by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The editors of the hymn versions are Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Krček.
On the server iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions.
For Bělohlávek, the Czech national song is one of the most beautiful hymns.
He had previously told the Czech radio that he had chosen singers with young, representative voices for the solo variations, which are striking and popular.
"From the beginning, I tried both and then with the choir to stick to a clear diction so that one can understand the text well so that a harmony can be created," says the conductor.
The Czech national anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj was first performed on stage in 1834 in the original Czech piece Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, by František Škroup.
It became popular, and people accepted it spontaneously.
The first verse of the song then became an organic component of the national anthem after the emergence of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
