The Prague transport companies transport for the first time on Wednesday also on a chip
Wednesday, October 1st, 2008 will be a date in the history of Prague's transport operations, when the first passengers will enter a metro, tram or bus that will carry an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
These can currently buy about one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or an annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) at the same time on their chip card, in the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
Since yesterday the coupons are also available via the Internet on the pages of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by over four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use the Internet sale can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they had to wait regularly in long queues for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon via Internet, it is played on the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these points there is also a desk with trained staff at the disposal of travellers, which advises those interested in the Internet purchase and also puts the coupon on the map," says Martin Opatrný, spokesperson for the project.
In addition to the libraries, the electronic coupons can also be played on the Opencard at self-service machines, which are installed in some subway vestibules.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket removers, the passengers may have noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"At the moment there are five of them in the city, but by the end of the year it is said to be eighty," Opatrný adds.
The Coupon is controlled by an automatic machine instead of the driver
The operation of the machines that will work from tomorrow is easy.
All you have to do is introduce the chip card, and the previously acquired coupon plays itself.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which the inhabitants of the municipalities of the region Mittelböhmen arrive in the capital.
"On trains belonging to Prague's integrated traffic, the train attendants have reading equipment with which they can check the validity of the coupons according to time and zone," explains Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid the ticket control. This organisation compiles the timetables for Prague's transport companies.
The suburban buses have card readers at the ticket office at the driver's office.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be shown to the driver, but the Opencard must be placed in a marked position on the side of the checkout.
The driver thus checks the validity of the played coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the played coupons, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information," says Drápal.
A passenger who does not drive by suburban buses and no longer knows when the validity of the coupon ends can go to the self-service machines, where the coupons are played on the card.
Here the information on the validity of its documents is displayed on the display of the device.
