A rat or a cockroach flees in case of danger, does that mean that she also feels fear?
The neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that a lot of animals also have feelings.
Only how could you check if they feel the same way when they behave like us?
The Internet magazine "Edge" has published articles by famous scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove this until now, where we can't even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we may at least hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and address questions of feeling or, more generally, of consciousness, we enter impassable terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat gets in danger, she does the same as many other animals: she turns herself dead, flees or attacks.
People behave similarly, which some scientists conclude is a comparable subjective experience.
I don't believe in that, though.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and in the execution / control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in humans than in the rest of primates and seems to be completely absent from other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is therefore reason to believe that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: since such a large part of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, however it may be, probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor analyzed on the basis of our own experience, because of the special hardware, then his research presents us with great problems.
Most of my remarks refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness, which should be more accessible scientifically.
One could examine the consciousness processes of animals without regard to their contents, and this is exactly what happens in studies of the short-term memory of primates, especially with regard to the example of visualization.
But in this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, one shifts rather to the neural correlations of consciousness than to the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What is the result of the sensations?
I refer them to the fact that an emotional system such as that of fear is activated in one of his own conscious brains.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies memory.
From this point of view, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the Cortex, which distinguish primates and especially humans.
Linked to the linguistic nature, fine gradations of feeling arise, because with the help of words and grammar we can differentiate and categorize states in order to ascribe them to others besides ourselves.
