The pride and the hardships in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden between the excesses of the amusement parks around Orlando, a few miles from the glittering, loud and gigantic hustle and bustle, there is a quiet city where the pride and complications of Afro-American culture can be seen.
Eatonville, the first completely black town in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquet places, 300 brown hides, 300 good swimmers, more than enough fish, 2 schools and no prison."
Today it is a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet the city that describes it - and which made it a tourist destination by taking it to the Florida travel guide, which was produced by the Federal Writer's Project at the time of depression - remains in many respects a very special kind of place.
Eatonville is as independent, dignified and private as in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he is missing."
Even today, in a year in which a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open discussion on racial relations, many here continue to be tired of being watched by outsiders.
"We are very concerned about how our story is told," says Hortense Jones, 59, from birth to a resident of the city and a member of the town's oldest church.
It must be true."
Eatonville was long defined as the paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of almost 2,400 inhabitants in which the poverty rate is twice as high as the national average.
It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other hand, an example of the - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - black culture of the rural south, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and alert.
And the concerns about Eatonville's image really started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973)
Five paragraphs in the Florida travel guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often forgotten center of Florida, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Naughty as Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the shop of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Away from the street to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-white-painted modern school, with its well-kept gardens and playgrounds, which Howard Miller always cares about, although he can hardly read and write."
She also mentioned the new husband of Widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sold drinks of any kind and what-also-always fits in with hourly rooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by all.
"Zora described things as they were," said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston by quoting the men singing songs about their beauty, full of sexual allusions.
She added, "Some people didn't like this."
One still remembers Hurtson as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembered that when Hurston was brewed into the city, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and wearing trousers, in a city that even today imagines something about its venerable style of clothing.
According to Mr. Franklin, most of the inhabitants were fascinated, while many despised them.
"People were always happy to see Zora," said Mr. Franklin.
But "she never stayed too long," he added as he rocked in his chair, on a back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Together with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville there was no great commemoration, no public readings in a large style.
"I don't think they have understood their contribution in the world or their inheritance in the least," says Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography about Hurston published in 2003.
The turn came in the 1980s.
Orange County authorities wanted to put a five-lane highway through the city to replace the Kennedy Boulevard, the slow two-lane main road of the municipality.
Orlando's suburbs had already pushed highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville still recovered from a difficult period in his history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the struggle against racial mixing brought hatred to the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys often came and they threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting away," said Mr. Franklin.
"There was even once a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In 1955, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's demand to force integration by calling its decision against the school council in the Brown case "insulting instead of respecting my race."
Inhabitants today say that although the abolition of racial segregation was positive in some respects, it weakened group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember - they hugged their teacher in the morning and they hugged their teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri , daughter of Ella Dinkins and managing director of the non-profit group to protect the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained for so long, she added, until teachers and students stopped coming from the same place.
"You didn't hug his white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural gap," said Ms. Nathiri.
However, civil rights have helped create space for more Zora Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors, and artists who ignored prejudice, as they did, with positive self-confidence and statements such as: "How can anyone refuse the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, the writer Alice Walker set out for Hurston's nameless grave and began to fight for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a highly acclaimed Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway was found on the bookshelves, and again made it part of the American literary canon.
The road project came exactly at a time when Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The municipality began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road plans.
"The plans of a five-lane highway enlivened the city, accelerated the whole thing at top speed, aroused real citizen pride," said Ms. Nathiri.
Ms. Boyd put it a little easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the highway project has contributed to a change in the city's image.
More and more people arrived, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to appreciate the past.
Eatonville was included in the national historical register in 1998.
A new one-storey library (of course named after Hurston) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville is still a peculiarity in Florida: only 6 miles from Orlando's city centre, it can sometimes feel like a back lane in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(She's 90% black these days.)
Outsiders in search of Eatonville's history and its significance are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, permission is necessary in advance and certain things - such as the wall painting of Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men in field work - must not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Mrs Jones, a courageous, confident teacher with a fondness for dark red, still fear that their shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival grew larger, an increased degree of home pride was also born.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better and as proud, creative and diligent, silly and mixed up as any other race and race group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who is planning to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city administration or the police, who could use some help according to him.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who only drive through here will think, "Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others," Alondra Kenon said the other day on a Sunday after the church.
"But if you actually stop and look at your story for a moment, it's a very nice city."
