Conversation - Of the blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
It is known that during the 1980s, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross's blood donation service were contaminated with the HIV virus and hepatitis C virus.
In view of this drama and public discontent, in February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation led by Judge Horace Krever aimed at bringing light to the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and drawing up guidelines to prevent a further catastrophe of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still reluctant to give his report, several provinces at that time set up a committee to develop a new system for the administration of preserved blood in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this task.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were founded in Canada: Hema-Quebec, who is in charge of Quebec, and the Canadian blood company, in order to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started work, almost 38% of people had confidence in the blood canning system in Quebec, remembers Dr. Décary.
The situation was disheartening.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood canning and through the work in this area during the following years, we have regained public confidence', she says, before she proudly stresses that at the beginning of 2008 almost 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its foundation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has been acting on the principle of caution.
At this time we witnessed the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman who has been in charge since its foundation in 1998.
'And we had no idea whether this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we referred to one of the main guidelines of Krever and Gélineau's reports, according to which exclusion measures are applied if one does not know this and if a disease progresses only slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is manifested by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from persons who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, it was without a doubt proven that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we used has a meaning.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which enable the virus itself to be detected directly in the donor's blood, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation period between the time when the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, explains the specialist.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors might be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize it, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is in danger of receiving HIV - infected blood.
'In other words, you have to distribute 12 million blood cans before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood cans every year, it would take more than 24 years before a case occurs in which HIV was transmitted via a blood can.
I believe that nowadays you can feel comfortable when you get a blood transfusion or prescribe it to restore your health,' says the director of Hema-Quebec.
'Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can get into the system.
Only last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by insects through the blood.
We need to monitor continuously," continues Dr. Décary, before she stresses that Hema-Quebec must also provide a sufficient supply in addition to a secure supply.
'The demand is increasing because the population is ageing.
As anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood supply network, which on average accounts for only 3% of Quebec's eligible population. '
Every healthy person who is 18 years or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people who provide their blood are not accepted because they are suffering from AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from blood donation for one year.
'With these 3%, we manage to get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they grow older and can no longer donate blood.
It's hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep it and get it to become regular donors.
Life today is so hectic that you rarely find the time to spend an hour in blood donation," Francine Décary regrets.
With an annual budget of $ 297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood canning, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is used almost exclusively for severe burn injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before they are temporarily stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only Quebec public cord blood bank.
In the umbilical cord, formerly considered biomedical waste, there is rich blood from stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
'A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to lose more than a thousand each year.
'We should probably start making it available for transplants at the beginning of next year', explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of umbilical cord decrease as very popular.
'Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it', because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
