Free Opinion - The Orwell Speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr Patrick J. Garver, Vice-Director General of the Canadian Gold Mine Barrick Gold.
This confirms, and pursues an Orwellian logic, that the world's largest gold mining company sought a slander lawsuit over six million against three authors and a small media-less publishing house with the aim of opening a 'public transparent debate'.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially not in the case of slander lawsuits, but of the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way is to have a public debate, to ruin anyone who dares to represent one of their opposite opinions.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and editors of Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid from the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactics of these unequal struggles are, moreover, often to ruin the defenders in order to force a consensual settlement that silences the opposite side and also deters anyone who dares to re-examine the question.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she should have presented her view of things before public opinion.
In contrast to what is common in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates are usually held in Canada through the exchange of ideas and not by billets.
So it would have been enough if the gold mine had disclosed its books and files and opened a real debate through the newspapers, media, publications and funding of independent review teams that could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and wipes aside the petitions and letters in support of Noir Canada's authors with a hand movement.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he can at the same time ask for a 'public' debate and yet disregard the opinions of this very public?
Apparently, in the vice-president's world, this word covers only the generously paid lawyers, not the community of all Canadians; a very narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public that supports the writers and editors of Noir Canada is doing so mainly because it rejects the brutal stance of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilised exchange of arguments, and not within a framework that many perceive as gags (in the course of the 'public debate', Barrick Gold has just addressed a demand to the authors of Noir Canada, in which it requires them not to use this term anymore...).
Apart from Mr Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's lawsuit is a direct attack on freedom of academic research and the truth-finding that is fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to quote credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to explore and discuss issues that the rich companies of this world do not like, who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could lead it by following the scientific standards used by Noir Canada's authors.
She has a right to reply.
The university environment we belong to has long known how to control debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
The disproportionate lawsuit by Barrick Gold clearly shows that, contrary to what it claims, it does not want a transparent debate.
This is a loss to the university world, as well as to the public debate, and it is time for governments to take measures to limit this kind of unjustified complaint.
Wall Street Rescue - Democrats and Republicans Understand
The Bush administration and the leading congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most extensive economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the plan to stop the financial crisis, which has been shaking Wall Street for months, has yet to be adopted by the two Congress Chambers.
The main points are: better control of Members of Parliament over the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to secure the repayment of the public funds used, new instruments to reduce the number of houses seized as a result of arrears, and the right to monitor the salaries paid to the managers of the supported companies.
The American finance secretary Henry Paulson, the President of the Chamber of Deputies Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative present at the negotiations, Senator Judd Gregg, announced yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, the good news, after a two-day negotiating marathon.
'We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective on the market', said the representative of the Bush administration, Henry Paulson.
'It all happened to protect the real economy and the American people from the price crisis on Wall Street,' said the Democrat.
'This is the fundamental point: if we do not do so, the trauma, chaos and unrest in the daily lives of Americans will be enormous,' said the Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had accelerated over the last two hours, for fear of the effect that a renewed failure would have on the mood of investors.
The deadline that had been agreed was the opening of the market this morning.
The two American presidential candidates, who only participated late in the negotiations, were more likely to support the agreement, but not to fail to express their dissatisfaction with the need to meet them in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barrack Obama insisted on the addition of certain dispositions to the agreement, especially those to enable the owners to keep their houses and those concerning the salaries of the executives of the companies saved by the State.
'If we ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain persons, that is nothing to which we could congratulate ourselves.
But these measures are necessary', he explained on the American television stations.
When asked on another channel whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied: 'I would like to know the details first, but I hope so.
'The guiding principles I have read show that this is one thing that we will all have to digest, and with which we will be able to advance.
The option of doing nothing is simply unacceptable,' he said.
The 700 billion dollar plan is aimed at providing taxpayers' money
It comes 14 months after a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble, which initially led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprime) before expanding to other forms of more widespread bonds (PCAA), and finally to a freeze of financial power and the ruins of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican MPs who failed last week's first attempt to reach agreement.
Since the Democrats have accepted that certain 'poisonous' assets of societies in distress should only be secured by the government and not bought, the dead end is believed to escape.
In order to round off the view for everyone in Congress, a provision has also been added which states that if the government should make losses with this program within five years, it could then levy new taxes in order to recover its invested capital.
The new plan provides for the payment of an initial sum of 250 billion, to which a further 100 billion may be added if the President considers it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion must be passed by Congress in a new vote.
In return for his help, Washington receives shares in the supported companies that pay dividends in the event of profits, and which it can sell again when the storm has passed.
The Federal Government will have the possibility to suspend the attachment proceedings relating to the dwellings linked to the real estate loans covered by this plan, and also to set time limits for the repayment and redemptions paid to the senior employees of the companies concerned.
The developers of the plan would like the Chamber of Deputies to vote on him today, and the Senate will vote on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will be given the green light.
In fact, more voices rose yesterday against this plan, both from the Republicans and the Democrats.
