The psychology of surpassing - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the offer.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to give themselves up in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play lottery while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined by functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the Striatum, a complex below the brain cortex, was measured in the losers of the auction, in which the opponent's outburst plays an essential role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore felt that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have also conducted research into the pursuit of the money.
In this case, three groups should compete against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their operations.
Another group was also promised $15 reward, in case they emerge as winners from the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was just that the emphasis on one was on winning, while the other was on losing.
However, as proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the group playing "against losing" were prepared for higher stakes than those in the control group or the "win" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
In fact, the behaviour observed at auctions has so far been based only on the joy of winning or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so that we now have a third explanation available," said Andrew Schotter, Professor of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should the doctor go?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is due to the fact that the patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and the diseases differ.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis virus spreads in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted by blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, vaginal secretion or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to use vaccination against the viruses A and B, there is no vaccine against the virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A are approximately two-three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
Afterwards, jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes light, the urine dark, and recovery can take up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from the far more severe diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten people are infected in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected people don't even know about their disease, as the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms show up after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who have had blood transfusions before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable during routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult the family doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
In time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thus eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the emergence of cancer.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, 2004 for the first time organized by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to increase awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their emergence and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
According to the latest research, religious faith seems like a kind of "pain cure" that has already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment: the extent to which faith in God influences human pain, the British paper "Telegraph" reported.
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
The results showed that the faithful were able to eliminate most of the pain.
By means of a brain scan technology, it was even proven that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for pain control.
The study was the first in a research project in which, in addition to scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university participate.
During the experiment, a sparkling device was attached to the left hand, which gave off the electric shocks.
The participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: on the one hand a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other Leonardo da Vinci's "Dame with Hermelin."
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary among the faithful would create a kind of religious trance, while they chose da Vinci's image, because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt soothing.
The subjects spent half an hour each in an MRI scanner, and during that time received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages, while they were to watch either the religious or the other painting.
Catholics reported that when they saw the Mother of God, they felt "in security, " as if they were" cared for, " and they felt "rest and peace. "
While viewing the religious painting, they reported 12% less pain than when they saw Leonardo's work in front of them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also took part in the experiment, said that similar effects could also be created with other, strong-acting images in the atheists, one simply had to find the corresponding photo.
"We need to find a picture that triggers very positive sensations, such as a mother or a father," says the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"Practising faith should change our personality, and in many cases it does," says Wright.
After these outstanding results, there remains only the question of what effect a Madonna image of Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the pain control of the faithful.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
