Intelligent car imitates the flight of bumblebees
What would be the best way to develop new accident prevention technologies if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
Like the bees.
At the CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented in which the Nissan engineers were inspired by bumblebees in the creation of new accident-avoiding systems.
In cooperation with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic system controlled by auto robots, a mini-car equipped with the bees' characteristics, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval "private area," which is very similar to our own "protective shield," said Kazuhhiro Doi, Product Manager for Technology PR and Research Development, at the exhibition.
The compound eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of more than 300 degrees, plays an important role.
In order to imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a visual field of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision-avoiding process.
The obstacle is registered in fractions of a second, and the auto robot immediately changes course, similar to the bees' movement by turning the tires around the appropriate angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
"If it weren't, the car robot couldn't react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and Autorobot Project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology is the most intuitive and vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are still considered unavoidable.
The entire process must reflect the bees' behavior when avoiding other bees.
And this has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, the evasiveness cannot go up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, only in the direction of the maneuverability of the tires.
While there are infinite possibilities for the bees to avoid other bees, the researchers were only able to use the rotational movement, respectively the acceleration and braking of the car robot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer lifespan than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh said it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process some inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It doesn't have to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction based on previous maneuvers, so it takes up only a handful of KB memory on an ongoing basis.
There's no need for gigabyte and megabyte-heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application could be the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately directing the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the goal.
