Today, the European Summit on Equal Opportunities has begun in Paris, which this year will be hosted by the EU Presidency of the Council of the European Union in France.
In her speech to the plenary, Lívia Járóka, Fidesz MEP of the European People's Party, drew particular attention to the segregation of education, as it is one of the most serious violations of the rights of Roma children, and it is also the greatest obstacle to their application.
The high-level conference was opened by French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs Xavier Bertrand on behalf of the French Presidency, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
The participants included representatives of governments, the European social partners, as well as the most important European legal protection and citizens' organisations in the field of equal opportunities.
According to the Fidesz Press Office, Járóka pointed out that, in addition to discrimination in job search, Roma were mainly displaced from the labour market because of their low level of education.
"The vast majority of Roma youths do not have middle-school education, and poor primary education means that only a small proportion of them can achieve a university degree."
Járóka also stressed that education is a fundamental human right, which would have a key role to play in asserting other human rights.
Investment in the early education of Roma children could strengthen the economy of EU member states.
In the opinion of the MEPs, it is important that these connections become as broad a circle as possible - Roma and non-Roma.
Because the earlier a Roma student starts school, the more his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market increase, and through income and VAT they contribute to national spending.
"As citizens of the Union, the right to high-quality education must be guaranteed to the Roma - the bad and segregated teaching must be stopped," said Lívia Járóka.
As the honourable Member said, a joint, objective and action-oriented approach by the European Union is necessary to accelerate the process of de-regation in the education sector, and to ensure that the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives are properly respected.
"We must break through the vicious circle of poverty, segregation, and unemployment, and give Roma children the democratic means to contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens," said Járóka.
Since last year's congress in Berlin, the summit has been held annually with the aim of creating a unique forum for promoting the objectives of equal opportunities and freedom of discrimination at European and national level, in the spirit of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities."
