Ukraine is becoming more and more economically dependent thanks to the rising prices of gas imports from Russia. In order to alleviate the price increases, loans have even been raised, and the country has also agreed to the sale of Beltransgas, the owner of the country's leading gas pipeline, to the Russians. Thus, in the background of the opposition's expectations, Ukraine hopes to improve its relationship with the EU after Lukashenko and other high-ranking politicians have banned entry into the EU because of the anti-democratic political system in the EU.
The evaluation report of the OECD elections provided a temporary relaxation, emphasising the positive movements rather than the shortcomings - such as the exclusion of one third of opposition candidates from the elections.
However, the Rapid Report of the OECD already criticized the campaign on Monday - so oppositionists should not appear in the press - and in particular the fact that the opposition was not allowed to be present in the counting of votes.
Despite all this, the opposition is able to see an improvement in the political system: political prisoners have been set free, and Minsk is even ready for smaller confrontations with Moscow by continuing to deny the recognition of the independence of the apostate Georgian provinces of South Ossetia and Abkhazia, although Russia, with which Ukraine on paper forms a federal state, considers the two territories independent for a month.
"We have taken two steps forward and one backwards, but the most important thing is that the dialogue between Belarus and the EU has begun," Alexander Milinkevich said to our paper.
According to the opposition candidate of the 2006 presidential elections, a continuation is desirable, although "the powerful have been afraid to let even one opposition member into parliament."
The opposition is not planning any protest measures in view of the results, but rather is trying to clarify the need for economic reform to the voters.
"We are struggling with many problems here - the oppositional newspapers must be printed in Russia, the local authorities are putting stones in our way in sales, but nevertheless I see that more and more people are supporting change, even the older ones," said Milinkevich in allusion to the fact that not even the most supported class of pensioners agrees with the Lukashenko regime, whose only merit is the production of social security.
"Thanks to the country's debt and the increase in the trade deficit, it is only a matter of time before the "social security" that is reminiscent of the silence of a cemetery begins to crumble," says Milinkevich.
In contrast to the opposition politician, Russian observers have called the elections democratic.
Sergei Lebedev, Head of the Mission of the Commonwealth of Independent States, said to the news agency Ria Novosti: "People believe the deeds, not the words." The absence of the opposition is therefore proof of the maturity of the Belarusian voters.
Brunetta: "From now on, breakfast is served before work"
For the first time in the history of Palazzo Chigi there are rotatable doors for the entrances and exits of the officials.
As of today, the measure will come into force against those smart people who first stamp and then go out drinking coffee during working hours.
The new anti-lazy law was presented today by Renato Brunetta, Minister of Public Administration and by Mauro Masi, Secretary General of the Presidency of the Council of Ministers.
">"Twisting doors are a means of increasing work efficiency through a higher attendance rate and more services," Minister Brunetta said.
"Now begins a new era of responsibility and transparency.
This is reformism," Brunetta underlines once again.
With the Palazzo Chigi, the establishment ends in all buildings of the Presidency of the Council of Ministers.
Masi says: "The choice of rotating doors is also of great symbolic value."
There was no resistance from the officials, the Secretary-General assured: "This process was supported by all, cooperation came from all sides."
All in all, there is now no breakfast during working hours; no more coffee or croissant.
Brunettas advises on this with a smile: "A good cappuccino at 7 o'clock works wonders."
During a meeting of the Scuola Superiore della Pubblica Amministrazione
of Rome the minister announces that "within three months the absences of officials have reduced to 50%, i.e. 60,000 people per year are more present at work."
He added that it was necessary to strengthen the efficiency of Italy's public administration
"Their wage dynamics - according to the Minister - have been twice as large as the private sector and far above the inflation rate over the last 8-10 years."
Meanwhile, thousands of officials have joined forces to counter the Brunetta decree in the context of the appeal supported by Codacons.
"While the Minister for the Civil Service is profiling himself with figures on lower absenteeism at work - according to the Consumer Centre - the people of 'working lazy people' are growing continuously.
In fact, thousands of correct and valuable civil servants have joined forces to declare war on the unlawful norms of the decree."
In particular, the Regional Administrative Court (TAR) is fighting for additional financial compensation for work-related illness, including the planned extension of the mandatory house arrest of the sick worker during which verification visits can be made and other aspects of the Minister's innovations are being challenged.
Napolitano: "Prevention against accidents at work is crucial"
Every day 2,500 accidents at work occur in Italy, three people die and 27 people remain disabled for life.
For 2007, the data from the Inail (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were around 1200.
These figures show the seriousness of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as those caused by murders.
Today, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Laworo) will celebrate the 58th National Day for the Victims of Accidents at Work in all the provinces of Italy in order to draw the attention of the social institutions and the media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data disseminated by Anmil and the tragic news of these days confirm how crucial the issue of workplace prevention is," confirms the President of the Republic of Giorgio Napolitano in his communication to the President of the Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The head of state expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to prevention in the workplace, to the protection of injured workers, to the support of the families of the victims and to the awareness of public opinion."
"A outraged "basta" has risen to this; understandable in the case of tragedies, which, in terms of their magnitude, trigger some vortexes in the media and public participation. But everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events, which can even be repeated in their own dynamics."
Napolitano does not hide the fact that "there is definitely also a resource problem: it must be invested decisively in education and information."
The numerous initiatives for a more direct awareness of the role of young people in the world of work are of particular importance.
It is our duty to focus attention on this phenomenon and not to distract it from its social seriousness. One must put into force and improve a legislative norm.
For his part, the President of the Chamber Gianfranco Fini stressed "how the phenomenon of work-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency, which offends the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work on firm rules that aim to put an end to the problem."
"The data on accidents at work seem to signal a slight improvement, but this does not rule out the fact that the number of work-related deaths is far too high," emphasizes President of Anmil, Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this "positive tendency" to mean less attention. That's what ultimately causes the tragedy."
"We believe that we are doing too little to counter the phenomenon of accidents, and we can fight it through various actions.
In our opinion, stronger controls and inspections are necessary - according to Mercandelli; but also stronger measures to inform the workers who are already starting at school."
"A further effort is needed - he adds - in terms of communication and awareness of public opinion.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers towards a phenomenon that is a social emergency is needed."
Mercandelli also referred to "the progressive deterioration of the protection of the victims of accidents at work" and denounced "the abolition of the social system against which we have been fighting in recent years."
"The aim is, therefore, to give the worker a guarantee on insurance so that the fate of the victim of an accident at work does not depend on voluntary or accidental donations, which from time to time are decided by a legislator."
Mp3 player under charge: danger of hearing damage
Listening to loud music over a longer period of time with portable music devices, such as Mp3 players, can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is reported by the European Commission, which in a report published today in Brussels quotes the opinion of the EU's Csrseri (scientific committee on current and recently identified health risks).
"The report, according to a note, makes it clear that 5-10% of those who listen to loud music with portable music devices for at least five years more than one hour a day per week risk the permanent loss of their hearing."
"I am worried that such a large number of young people, who usually place portable music devices and mobile phones at a high volume, will irretrievably damage their hearing without knowing it," says Meglena Kuneva.
"From the scientific findings - it is said on the part of the Eu - there is a clear risk that pushes for quick action.
What really matters is to sensitize consumers and make this information a common good.
In the light of these scientific findings, we need to re-examine the already existing control systems so that they are fully effective and keep pace with the new technology."
In view of the widespread use of portable music equipment among young people, Brussels had commissioned the independent scientific committee.
"Scientists - the EU communication concludes - confirm that we are quite concerned and that the Eu Commission, together with the other Eu-members and stakeholders, will now examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise from portable music devices and similar devices."
There is already a European standard, which limits the level of noise from portable music equipment to 100 dB, and concerns about the damage that could result from excessive noise pollution.
One can limit these damages very much, in which one reaches solutions such as the reduction of the volume and the length of the noise output.
In their report, the scientific committee of the Eu points out that when users of portable music devices listen only five hours a week loud ( louder than 89 decibels) music, so that the legal limits that apply to the maximum noise level at the workplace are already exceeded.
Those who exceed this limit risk the complete loss of hearing within five years.
This therefore affects 5-10% of users of such devices, whose number can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the Eu.
Roma, Alemanno launches the "Commission for the Future of the Capital"
We're starting today, we're supposed to be over in March, and we're taking stock in June.
This is the process laid down by the Capitol for the work of the "Commission for the Future of the Capital of Rome," and the Commission met this morning in the new seat behind the Caracalla thermal baths.
In six months, President Marzano and the other 49 members of the Commission will work out the leadership lines for Rome.
Once the project is completed, the City Council and the Municipal Council will evaluate the analyses and projects in order to be able to present the strategic plan for Rome with the "official stamp" of the Capitol and the Lord Mayor Gianni Alemanno in June.
"The Commission is absolutely independent and all political, social and cultural opinions are represented in it," - Alemanno emphasizes. "It will present proposals for a development plan for Rome, whose political leaders remain the City Council and the Municipal Council.
There is no redistribution of responsibilities, only the will to have a place where one can develop a large project for Rome.
In March, their task will be completed and the Commission will dissolve again, as such a project must have a timed end point.
In June - as the mayor announces - we will present the strategic plan in which we will make use of the work done by the Commission."
Those who question the Commission's competence, because they lack a sense of commitment, reply Alemanno: "Everything depends on the work that the Commission will do and on the quality of its proposals.
If, like the Attali Commission in France, it delivers quality results - and this will certainly be the case in Rome - then its contribution will be fundamental.
Too often politics deals with the everyday problems and emergencies that arise from time to time.
We, on the other hand, want to have a longer period of time in view of working seriously on the development of Rome and the future of the city in a deeper perspective."
The mayor of Rome attaches great importance to clarifying the following: "This commission is neither a useless institution nor a wreck: it is absolutely free of charge, it will not cost the Roman citizens a cent and it will make us think. It will occupy the best minds of the capital."
According to Alemanno, "it is necessary to have a strategic plan that is neither hermetic nor static to enable our city to make a leap in quality - which it really needs - and thus to take a joint step into the future."
A future, according to the mayor of Rome, "which will not only be limited in the current municipal borders but will look much further," not only in terms of Rome's role as a metropolis and political capital of Italy, but also as a future capital of Europe and the Mediterranean."
