The elite are in danger
The phenomenon had already been revealed a few days ago when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the 700 billion-dollar White House savings package: a large part of Americans were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday's issue of the New York Times, which reports how the crisis in progress divides the Republican Party, which is increasingly divided into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favoured state institutions and the business community, and those neo-conservatives who are hostile to "them in Washington" and the financial world and, above all, win voters in the south and the center of the states.
This part of the party owes its ascension, above all, to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
However, this example just mentioned is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake announces or even already represents: not only in the US, also throughout the West and perhaps beyond it will be affected by it.
Both in the States and in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the long feared events that are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the unheard-of renaissance of the state in conjunction with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
Indeed, the crisis means a decline in banking and financial institutions, which have close links with foreign countries and at the same time manage an enormous amount of the wealth of households living in a single state.
This means a direct political problem for governments: how to behave towards the families affected, which is an enormous number of voters.
So the crisis seems to be global in economic terms, but politically, it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have fallen into the dark in itself and lost its right to speak: the obvious proof of this has been given by the EU, which, due to its division into different national and international conflicts, cannot find a common path.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and especially the distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis became more and more serious, only the US is in the economic situation to save itself without foreign aid.
In addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus, two conditions that cannot be overvalued - under certain circumstances - which otherwise no international organisation or market will be able to rely on in a similar way.
The new emphasis placed on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance recently associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is precisely now that we were so convinced that we had long since entered a networked global realm, a realm of increasingly differentiated technologies, of intangibles, that we suddenly have to determine how our future will increasingly depend on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
These can certainly all be transported from one place to the other in the world, but are nevertheless connected to a closely circumscribed piece of earth - a territory.
Therefore, the one who has such a territory is in favour of another who lives in a cropless, waterless or oil-free area.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a short insertion.
Whoever says territory, who government, who politics also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, that is, the need for someone who knows how to regulate things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation about the existing leaderships, especially those of the economy, which have turned out to be inadequate and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and, in some sense, even more disturbing aspect: a loss of confidence, an intolerantness, an image of inexpensiveness, a sense of distance, all directed towards a whole class of managers in the Western countries.
The conviction among large sections of the population seems to pave the way, that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content is presented to the majority as increasingly alien and more advanced.
The demand for leadership thus feeds underground a branched but powerful movement of disempowerment of the leading class and of the traditional political establishment. This manifests itself in unforeseen "revolutions" of voters and in the unmediated change of the collective state of mind of recent times: starting with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, over the collapse of the Labour Party in Britain, towards the rebellion of the American MPs against Bush (and perhaps also the victory of the right in Italy plays a role here).
One gets the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say their format, more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value as to what is going on in the lower social strata of the West today and is being intensified from the financial crisis and driven to over-dimensionality.
In view of all this, it would simply be exaggerated to speak of a "rebellion of the masses."
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
The super glue that blows up on walls
To defeat the forces of gravity thanks to an adhesive and to be able to climb walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centres, one of which seems to have almost reached its goal.
With an adhesive applied on an area of only 2.5 sq.m., the researchers succeeded in fixing a body weighing 100 kg on a vertical wall.
The STUDIO - an American magazine has published the results of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the research team is a further development of the adhesives already used, which use a special carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged into a pile of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang from the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists have been inspired by the feet of the geckos, which are covered by microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect hold.
The tests carried out with different materials such as glass Teflon and sanding paper have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the holding ability of the reptile's feet and at the same time "can easily be removed from the wall," says Liming Dai, researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
"This material could be used as a transitory adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Like Spiderman, it's like going up on walls? Perhaps, but the researchers are thinking of a less fascinating benefit, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other areas of application could be in the space sector.
So for now, the superheroes still have to wait.
THE OTHER TYPE OF RESEARCH - including the University of Berkeley, California, is dedicated to a new type of glue.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, the Californian scientists present an adhesive made of microfibres that cleans itself of the dust like hair by moving on a surface and thus always preserves perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Be careful of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed in the summer due to their refreshing quality and vitamin richness, can cause serious health damage when taken at the same time with certain vital drugs, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points to the risk of packaged and fresh fruit juices in connection with medication intake. At the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he once again raised the alarm: it is enough for a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital drugs to the extent that they are practically eliminated and thus endanger the health of the patients.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected to be responsible for increasing the effects of some medicines, such as antibiotics, anti-asthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, to toxic levels.
In a report two years ago, the same agency of the medicine had warned doctors and patients of the dangers of this mix and stressed the need to take care of what is being drunk with drugs such as Diazepan or Metadon.
IT'S NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT - According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the medicines.
The list of active substances inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Therefore, Michele Carruba, Director of the Statale di Milano University, appealed: "Such results are usually immediately passed on to the various international manufacturers, who are so free to change the consumer information.
Therefore, it is advisable to read the package leaflet at all times and, if there are still uncertainties, do not be afraid to ask a pharmacist or doctor," emphasizes the Ansa agency's expert.
Nobel Prize in Economics goes to Paul Krugman
The Nobel Prize in Economics is awarded to the American Paul Krugman for his analysis of trade patterns and the settlement of economic activities.
The 55-year-old Krugman is a Neokeynesian who teaches at the University of Princeton and is known for his regular articles for the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the biggest critics of the Bush administration's economic and foreign policy.
A few months after the attacks of September 11, 2001, during the days of the Enron collapse, Krugman claimed in an editorial of the New York Times that this second event had been more crucial to the history of the United States than the attacks.
A prediction, which received not a little polemic in response and was held before the economist years later, but today proves to be completely correct.
"I am surprised and also shocked at how quickly the memory of the scandals in the context of the collapses of Enron or Worldcom has disappeared from the public eye," Krugman explained at the end of 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is an "economy of great value," but also a banalizer with a "very aggressive style that is particularly directed against the excessive liberalism of the Bush administration."
Open Office, the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package appears
The OpenOffice.org 3.0 release date has come; as a free replacement for Microsoft's Office, the open source software gains an ever-increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in public administration.
After a year of intensive work by the voluntary developers, which is monitored by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office is now presenting itself to the audience with some innovations: in addition to a revised and now spartan-designed initial menu, a completely guaranteed compatibility with Apple's operating system Mac OS x has finally been achieved, as well as the support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, i.e. the latest standard ISO version.
Eight of them were also compared to compatibility with Microsoft's Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Also interesting are some new features, such as the one that allows to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which facilitates e.g. sending via email. This also includes the possibility to import PDF files into graphics editing modules and at the same time preserve the original appearance of the page.
Thus, "hybrid" PDF files can now be generated, which extend the typical graphics of the Adobe format by the elements of a table and a word processing system.
The collaboration is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be processed by several hands by different users, thus avoiding conflicts in the event of changes; in the case of the word processing system, each processor is assigned a frame to guarantee a better correction procedure.
Some companies are about to publish various functions of OpenOffice on the Internet (on the cloud), while in the coming weeks the final result will be made public.
The Italian version is available on the following link for download: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html. Thus it follows the English version, which has been on the mirrors since Friday.
Except for Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
Upon request you can send the installation CD home or to the office.
However, if freedom of charge can be an incentive for the distribution of the programme in private households, it is also in the field of business, where OpenOffice could succeed in the big challenge: after all, various institutions of public administration and schools have already moved to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of training offer, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized enterprises, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word corresponding text creation program; Calc, the table program that aims to displace Excel; Impress, to create presentations such as Powerpoint; Dbase to operate databases in place of the better known access; and finally Draw, a graphics module.
The goal for 2008 is to achieve 5 million downloads - a goal that can easily be exceeded with already reached 3 million and 600 thousand.
Kohl also tested positively and thus the fourth doping case
