Students victims of up to 900 euros per room high rental prices
The market for apartments for students knows no crises.
According to the last survey by the Sunia, the tenant union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 euros in Florence, 650 euros in Naples and 600 euros in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken on very serious proportions. In fact, a whole host of students lose their right to study, because their families are unable to support them at this level," says Laura Mariani, who is responsible for Sunia, "in these cities, the great demand from students leads to a deformity of the market, which has also damaged the other inhabitants.
In addition, most rental offers include a number of infringements: free contracts, missing registrations, without rental price limit, unauthorized sub-renting.
There is a need for exceptional measures for Sunia, which lead to lower rental prices by revising taxation.
On closer examination of the study it turns out that in Milan a sleeping place in the neighborhood Brianza is needed about 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the neighborhood Nere) and ends at 800 euros in the neighborhood Lambiate, Udine and Fiera or even 900 euros in the neighborhood Vittoria.
In Florence an average sleeping place costs 350/400 euros, a room 700.
In Bologna, where the students concentrate in the neighborhoods around the university, are 250/280 euros for a sleeping place of need, 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome the prices in the neighborhoods around the university are about 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a sleeping place in a double room.
The rents in the neighborhoods around the other universities of Rome are only slightly lower: 550 euros in Ostiense and Cinecittà.
Only those who avoid in outskirts can save money: 300 euros for a sleeping place and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar quarters.
In Naples you need 300-450 euros for a sleeping place, for a room the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive neighborhoods, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari a sleeping place costs 250-350 euros, a single room at least 350 euros.
In the smallest cities, prices are lower, but they are more important in the urban economy.
In cities where the phenomenon of renting out to non-European students is more common, such as Perugia, there is even another anomaly: foreign students are required to rent 25-30% more than the average.
Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso - the cities close their historic cinema halls
The historical cinemas close due to the beneficiary multiplexkinos.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture by director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the major urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of the exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-saal complexes in the periphery, in the long run means death for the one-saalkino in the centre. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also bears the traits of cultural crime.
Most of them are affected by historical places full of memories, "it's like losing a friend with whom one has covered a piece of street full of emotions," according to the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso," who 20 years ago brought him the Oscar and the great prize of Cannes. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a world of cinema that is probably lost forever.
The figures supplied by Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; most of these cinemas paid for in the big cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are the multiplexkinos, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: at 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy lists, 81 in Tuscany as well as in Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, President of Anec, "it is useful that new structures also emerge, but first of all the preservation of the already existing one, because if a hall closes in the city, not all of its regular customers are ready to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here remains the missing budget for the fund of the trade association outside eight: the debt burden recorded by the state amounts to about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from the ethical-moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
In order to preserve the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros in the year would be needed."
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, because of the fears surrounding the old cinema halls, decided to protect it by an agreement between the municipality and Anec; it is the first such agreement in Italy to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the measures envisaged are also tax advantages for cinema operators, as well as benefits for the public regarding local transport: it will be allowed to travel to the limited traffic areas of the centre and to park at more favourable parking fees.
"It is a pleasing initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will follow our example and also develop new concepts.
But certainly we also need better audio and video equipment to be able to do something against the superpower of the multiplex halls, because after all, the audience of today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the crucial point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso," even though I had been playing with the idea for 10 years.
For 25 years I have been living in Rome; when I pass by the Rialto or Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside in order not to have to see the dust-covered posters.
The links between politics and 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to adapt the community's decisions to the interests of the Piromalli Mafia group.
The charges against Mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of the municipality of Gioia Tauro, who were arrested this morning for involvement in mafia business, are serious.
Gioacchino Piromalli, the elder mediator between the clan and the public administration, and his nephew were also handcuffed: the lawyer, who bears the same name as the boss of the clan, had already been convicted of involvement in criminal associations of the mafia, at the time to a compensation sum of 10 million euros.
"Every kind of moral and legal norm disregarding," writes the lawyers, "the two local administrations had decided to pay the lawyer Priomalli money for consulting activities."
"It was thus made possible for the Mafia group - according to the judges - to enter the town halls on an official way and to agree on the politics of public administration."
The President of the Calabrian Regional Committee, Agazio Loiero, does not deny that in his region "it is anything but an exception to encounter links between local administrations and organised crime." "There are places in which the concentration of the mafia is greater than in others in which such links are virtually inevitable.
But there are also local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'Ndrangheta: heroes who get a white vest'.
The arrests of this morning follow those of last July, which according to the police of the Clan Piromalli was beheaded.
Since the end of April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved, but already in 1991 - and even then due to alleged links between organized crime and local administration - the local politicians had been removed from their municipal offices.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, then mayor of the Udc, was elected head of the centre-right coalition after the May 2006 election.
He screamed scandal when the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipal council.
He called on Vice-Minister Marco Minniti, whom he accused of inventing everything for political and strategic reasons, but the judges, in connection with this morning's arrest warrant, declare that the Priomalli clan had even dared to apply for an amendment to the A3 project.
From an interrogation in connection with the Dal Torrione case, the willingness to respond to the wishes of an entrepreneur who is known to be a representative of the large group around the Piromalli - thus making the public administration's actions identical to the interests of this clan."
When the energy comes out of the waves, the big ones suddenly rise
It is a non-destructive source of money that covers more than 70% of the planet's surface, and only now do the world's big energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and also seeking to occupate, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years; it is not by chance that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980 the idea of marine energy was gassed, but now the environmental organizations and the increased oil price are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world's energy needs could be met by ocean wave energy.
This would be equivalent to twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there are also the currents and tides.
Giants at the attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy is Enersis, who signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, there are now more and more companies from the traditional energy sector that rely on marine energy production.
"Chevron investigates these technologies" - according to the spokesman of a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal - and weighs the possibility of working with us."
This is about obtaining an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign that cannot be underestimated, especially considering that oil is still being extracted by the US in Alaska, and that President Bush has just begun plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; even the details are not known, so observers speak of an increasing interest.
Technologies that are still worth improving.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still emerging, not least because the last doubts on the part of environmentalists have not yet been resolved.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of a rather small scale and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with far greater influence on the environment are needed.
There are several options: Ocean Power uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floats via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned facilities of this kind, which are only waiting for state approval. Some of the energy gained could also be used for military facilities.
However, Verdant Power is already producing energy for a department store and a parklatz using submarine turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feeds the generator by the resulting rotational motion.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorization to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Generation Research, special interest is immediately worthy of the potential that is in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and waves, and therefore a more trustworthy source of electricity.
It is the tidal energy that led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska as well as other coastal states to invest already 7.5 million dollars in 2008 - up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
